  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are international laws and agreements aimed at preventing money laundering. Some key examples include:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations, which set global standards for combating money laundering\n\n2. The United Nations Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n\n3. The Palermo Convention, which provides a framework for international cooperation against organized crime\n\n4. Various international banking regulations that require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n\n5. The International Money Laundering Information Network (IMoLIN)\n\nThese frameworks require countries to criminalize money laundering, implement reporting mechanisms, and cooperate in investigations across borders. While enforcement varies, most developed countries have strict anti-money laundering (AML) laws and regulations.",
